solution:
Using long division,
\[
\begin{array}{c|ccccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{y^3} & -\frac{2}{3}y^2 & +\frac{11}{9}y&-\frac{95}{27}  \\
\cline{2-6}
3y-2 & 3y^4 & -4y^3& +5y^2&-13y&4  \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{3y^4} & -2y^3& \\ 
\cline{2-3}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & -2y^3& +5y^2\\ 
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -2y^3& +\frac{4}{3}y^2\\ 
\cline{3-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0& +\frac{11}{3}y^2 & -13y\\ 
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & +\frac{11}{3}y^2 & -\frac{22}{9}y\\ 
\cline{4-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & &0 & -\frac{95}{9}y & +4\\ 
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & -\frac{95}{9}y & +\frac{190}{27}\\ 
\cline{5-6}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 0 & -\frac{82}{27}\\ 
\end{array}
\]So the remainder is $\boxed{-\frac{82}{27}}$.

Using the quadratic formula, we find that the roots of the quadratic are $\frac{-7\pm\sqrt{7^2-4(4)(k)}}{8}=\frac{-7\pm\sqrt{49-16k}}{8}$. Since the problem tells us that these roots must equal $\frac{-7\pm\sqrt{15}i}{8}$, \begin{align*} \sqrt{49-16k}&=\sqrt{15}i
\\\Rightarrow\qquad \sqrt{49-16k}&=\sqrt{-15}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 49-16k&=-15
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 16k&=64
\\\Rightarrow\qquad k&=\boxed{4}.
\end{align*}

By the Binomial Theorem,
\begin{align*}
(z + i)^4 &= z^4 + 4z^3 i + 6z^2 i^2 + 4zi^3 + 1 \\
&= z^4 + 4iz^3 - 6z^2 - 4iz + 1.
\end{align*}So, if $z^4 + 4z^3 i - 6z^2 - 4zi - i = 0,$ then
\[(z + i)^4 = z^4 + 4iz^3 - 6z^2 - 4iz + 1 = 1 + i.\]Let $w = z + i,$ so $w^4 = 1 + i.$  (If we plot the solutions $w$ in the complex plane, we obtain the same area as from the solutions $z$ in the complex plane, because the substitution $w = z + i$ simply translates the polygon.)

If $w^4 = 1 + i,$ then
\[(wi)^4 = w^4 i^4 = w^4 = 1 + i.\]Thus, if $w$ is a solution, then so are $iw,$ $i^2 w = -w,$ and $i^3 w = -iw,$ which form a square in the complex plane.

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = 2^(1/8)*dir(45/4);
B = 2^(1/8)*dir(45/4 + 90);
C = 2^(1/8)*dir(45/4 + 180);
D = 2^(1/8)*dir(45/4 + 270);

draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw((-1.5,0)--(1.5,0));
draw((0,-1.5)--(0,1.5));

dot("$w$", A, E);
dot("$iw$", B, N);
dot("$-w$", C, W);
dot("$-iw$", D, S);
[/asy]

From the equation $w^4 = 1 + i,$ $|w^4| = |1 + i|.$  Then $|w|^4 = \sqrt{2},$ so $|w| = 2^{1/8}.$  Therefore, the side length of the square is
\[|w - iw| = |w||1 - i| = 2^{1/8} \sqrt{2} = 2^{5/8},\]so the area of the square is $(2^{5/8})^2 = 2^{5/4}.$  The final answer is $5 + 4 + 2 = \boxed{11}.$

Since $5^2+12^2=13^2$, triangle $AEB$ is a right triangle.  Define $F$ to be the foot of the perpendicular drawn from $E$ to side $AB$.  The distance from $E$ to side $AD$ is $AF$.  By the similarity of triangles $AEF$ and $ABE$, \[
\frac{AF}{AE}=\frac{AE}{AB}.
\]Solving for $AF$, we find $AF=AE^2/AB=5^2/13=\boxed{\frac{25}{13}} = \boxed{1\frac{12}{13}}$ units.

