solution:
Since $39 = 2 \times 18 + 3$, the $39$th digit past the decimal point is the same as the $3$rd digit past the decimal point. To find this, we can directly divide: $$
\begin{array}{c|cccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & .0 & 5 & 2 \\
\cline{2-5}
19 & 1 & .0 & 0 & 0 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 9 & 5 & \downarrow \\ \cline{2-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 5 & 0 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 3 & 8 \\ \cline{4-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 1 & 2 \\
\end{array} $$ Thus, the answer is $\boxed{2}$.

Let $r = 1994.$  The line joining the center $(0,0)$ to $(a,b)$ is perpendicular to the line joining $(2r,2r)$ to $(a,b).$  Hence, the product of their slopes is $-1.$

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

pair O, P, T;

O = (0,0);
P = (2,2);
T = ((1 + sqrt(7))/4,(1 - sqrt(7))/4);

draw(Circle((0,0),1));
