Since $P$ lies on the circle with diameter $\overline{F_1 F_2},$ $\angle F_1 PF_2 = 90^\circ.$  Then by Pythagoras,
\[(F_1 F_2)^2 = x^2 + y^2.\]Squaring the equation $x + y = 15,$ we get $x^2 + 2xy + y^2 = 225.$  Then $x^2 + y^2 = 225 - 2xy = 225 - 2 \cdot 52 = 121,$ so $F_1 F_2 = \boxed{11}.$

Let the sum be $S$.  We can split this into 2 geometric series:
\begin{align*}
S &= \left( \frac{1}{7} + \frac{1}{7^2} + \frac{1}{7^3} + \cdots \right) + \left( \frac{1}{7^2} + \frac{1}{7^4} + \frac{1}{7^6} + \cdots \right) \\
  &= \frac{1/7}{1-1/7} + \frac{1/49}{1-1/49} \\
  &= \frac{1/7}{6/7} + \frac{1/49}{48/49} \\
  &= \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{48} \\
  &= \boxed{ \frac{3}{16} }
\end{align*}

Let $x = AD.$

