A = (-5,3);
B = (7,-2);
Z = (6,6);

draw(A--B);
draw(A--Z--B);

dot("$-5 + 3i$", A, NW);
dot("$7 - 2i$", B, SE);
dot("$z$", Z, NE);
[/asy]

By the Triangle Inequality, the sum of the distances is minimized when $z$ lies on the line segment connecting the two complex numbers $-5 + 3i$ and $7- 2i,$ in which case the sum of the distances is simply $|(5 - 3i) - (-7 + 2i)| = |12 - 5i| = \boxed{13}.$

To perform division in complex numbers, we multiply both the numerator and the denominator by the conjugate of the denominator. In this case, the conjugate of $1+2i$ is $1-2i$. Multiplying: \begin{align*}
\frac{-3+4i}{1+2i}&=\frac{(-3+4i)(1-2i)}{(1+2i)(1-2i)}\\
&=\frac{-3+4i+6i-8i^2}{1+2i-2i-4i^2}\\
&=\frac{5+10i}{5}\\
&=\boxed{1+2i}
\end{align*}

